UK Brigadier James Woodham sealed the handover by shaking hands with US Brigadier General Daniel Yoo, who said Britain's sacrifice would go down in 'the annals of military history'.

Senior commanders say the Afghan army and police forces are increasingly able to maintain security.

But they warn that the threat of casualties will endure until the last soldier leaves. National elections on Saturday provide the first flashpoint.

Four hundred troops representing every unit in the task force attended the Camp Bastion ceremony, staged in front of a monument bearing 16 plaques – one for each brigade to fight there.

Padre Steve Whiting said: 'From the poppy fields of Ypres to those of Helmand province, our bravest and best have borne the cost of freedom for others.'

Brigadier Woodham, who commands 7 Armoured Brigade – the Desert Rats – said Britain should feel proud of its troops despite the mission's painful losses.

